<subsection>
	<title>Theorems Related to Fourier Series</title>
	<theorem>
		<statement>
			<p>
				The quantity <m>||F-F_N||^2</m> on the interval <m>[-\pi,\pi]</m> is the minimum if and
				only if the coefficients of <m>F_N</m> in (2) ar the Fourier coefficients of <m>F</m>.
				This minimum value is
			</p>

			<p>
				<men xml:id="eq-estar">
					E^{\star} = \int_{-\pi}^{\pi} f^2 \, dx - 2A_0\pi - \pi \sum_{n=1}^{N} (A_n^2 + B_n^2)
				</men>
			</p>
		</statement>
	</theorem>
	<theorem
	xml:id="thm-bessels-inequality">
	<title>Bessel's Inequality</title>
	<statement>
		<p>
			Let <m>a_0, a_n</m> and <m>b_n</m> be the fourier coefficients related to the function <m>
			f</m> on <m>[-\pi,\pi]</m>.
			Then
		</p>

		<p>
			<me>
				2a_0^2 + \sum_{n=1}^N (a_n^2+b_n^2) \leq \frac{1}{\pi} \int_{-\pi}^{\pi} f^2 \, dx
			</me>
		</p>
	</statement>
</theorem>
<theorem
xml:id="thm-parsevals-theorem">
<title>Parseval's Theorem</title>
<statement>
	<p>
		Let <m>a_0, a_n</m> and <m>b_n</m> be the fourier coefficients related to the function <m>
		f</m> on <m>[-\pi,\pi]</m>.
		Then
	</p>

	<p>
		<me>
			2a_0^2 + \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} (a_n^2+b_n^2) = \frac{1}{\pi} \int_{-\pi}^{\pi} f^2 \, dx
		</me>
	</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<p>
	There
	are two important consequences of this theorem:
</p>

<p>
	<ul>
		<li>
			<p>
				If the integral on the right side is finite, then the series on the left converges.
				Functions in which the right side is finite are piecewise continuous functions.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				The error, <m>E^{\star}</m> in (<xref ref="eq-estar" />) goes to zero.
				That is Fourier
				Series converge to <m>f</m> (using the square error).
			</p>
		</li>
	</ul>
</p>

<example>
	<statement>
		<p>
			Calculate <m>E^{\star}</m> for the function:
		</p>

		<p>
			<me>
				f(x) = \begin{cases}
				\pi+x \amp x \in [-\pi,0) \\
				\pi-x \amp x \in [0,\pi]
				\end{cases}
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			and extended periodically and let <m>N=5,10,25,50,100,250,500,1000</m>.
		</p>
	</statement>

	<solution>
		<p>
			The Fourier Series of this function is
		</p>

		<p>
			<me>
				f(x) = \frac{\pi}{2} + \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{2}{\pi n^2} (1-(-1)^n) \cos nx
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			or <m>a_0 = \pi/2</m> and <m>a_n = (2/\pi n^2)(1-(-1)^n) </m>
		</p>

		<p>
			<md>
				<mrow>E^{\star} \amp = \int_{-\pi}^{\pi} f^2 \, dx - 2A_0\pi - \pi \sum_{n=1}^{N} (A_n^2
				+ B_n^2) </mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 2\int_{0}^{\pi} (\pi-x)^2 \, dx - 2\biggl(\frac{\pi}{2}\biggr) - \pi
				\sum_{n=1}^{N}\biggl(\frac{2}{\pi n^2} (1-(-1)^n) \biggr)</mrow>
			</md>
		</p>

		<table>
			<title></title>
			<tabular>
				<row>
				<cell>
				<m>n</m>
				</cell>
				<cell>
				<m>E^{\star}</m>
				</cell>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell>
				5 </cell>
				<cell> 0.00372 </cell>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell>10 </cell>
				<cell> 0.000832 </cell>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell>25 </cell>
				<cell> 0.0000482 </cell>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell>50 </cell>
				<cell>
				<m>6.78 \times 10^{-6} </m>
				</cell>
				</row>
				<row>
				<cell>100 </cell>
				<cell>
				<m>8.49 \times 10^{-8} </m>
				</cell>
				</row>
				<row>
