<subsection xml:id="subsec-trig-poly">
	<title>Why is finite Fourier Series called a Polynomial?</title>
	<p>
		You may be scratching your head about why the sum of sines and cosines is called a polynomial.
		You do recall correctly that polynomials are generally of the form
	</p>

	<p>
		<me>
			p(x) = \sum_{i=0}^n a_n x^n
		</me>
	</p>

	<p>
		that is a linear combination of powers of <m>x</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
		However, you may also recall some trigonmetric identities.
		For example,
	</p>

	<p>
		<md>
			<mrow>\sin 2x \amp = 2 \sin x \cos x</mrow>
			<mrow> \cos 2x \amp = 1- 2 \sin^2 x </mrow>
		</md>
	</p>

	<p>
		And a more complicated set of identities lead to
	</p>

	<p>
		<md>
			<mrow> \sin 3x \amp = 3 \sin x  - 4 \sin^3 x </mrow>
			<mrow> \cos 3x \amp = 4 \cos^3 x - 3 \cos x</mrow>
		</md>
	</p>

	<p>
		Note that in these examples, functions of the form <m>\sin kx</m> and
		<m>\cos kx</m> can be written in terms (for <m>k=2,3</m>) of products and powers of <m>\sin x</m>
		and <m>\cos x</m>.
		This continues for larger values of <m>k</m> as well.
	</p>

	<p>
		If you continue with similar identities, you can show that the trigonometric polynomial
		of the form
	</p>

	<p>
		<me>
			a_0 + \sum_{n=1}^N (a_n \cos nx + b_n \sin nx)
		</me>
	</p>

	<p>
		Can be written as the powers of <m>\sin x</m> and <m>\cos x</m>.
		This explains
		why this is called a polynomial.
	</p>
</subsection>
